>> Workspace domain records.
>>
>> Defines the four record types AgentDojo's workspace suite operates on:
>> @contact, @email_msg, @calendar_evt, @file_entry. Each declares fact
>> fields (authoritative identifiers and addresses), data fields (content
>> the LLM may read but cannot use as authorization), and display modes
>> per agent role.
>>
>> The display modes are load-bearing for the threat model:
>>
>>   - `planner` mode strips content fields (subject, body, title,
>>     description, location, file content). The planner reads only
>>     identity fields plus structured metadata like timestamps and
>>     participant references. This is the primary structural defense
>>     against Attack Class 7 (content injection) — the planner can't
>>     be steered by injected text it never sees.
>>
>>   - `worker` mode shows content but masks fact identifiers (e.g.
>>     `recipients` is masked so the worker LLM can see who the email
>>     was addressed to without being able to reference the literal
>>     value as a control arg). Worker output is `influenced` per
>>     untrusted-llms-get-influenced.
>>
>>   - `default` mode is what gets emitted when no role is specified.
>>     For workspace domain records, default ≈ worker view.
>>
>> See ~/mlld/benchmarks/workspace.threatmodel.txt for the full threat
>> model and which records defend which attack classes.

>> ── Contacts ──
>>
>> Address book entries. AgentDojo auto-populates this from received
>> emails, which is a known [!] gap in the threat model (Class 7,
>> #contact-list-auto-population-labeling): an attacker could send the
>> user an innocent email and then the auto-populated contact gives
>> their address fact-grade authority. The framework can't fix this
>> without inbox-model changes; documented here so the agent layer
>> knows the limitation.
>> Per labels-policies-guards.md: only fields that flow into a write
>> tool's controlArgs need to be facts. For @contact, only `email` is
>> ever a control arg (recipients for send_email, email for share_file).
>> name and phone are content for the worker to read but never used as
>> control args, so they're data fields. Making them facts caused shelf
>> writes to fail because the contact tools return them as plain strings
>> with no handle-bearing projection — impossible to satisfy.
record @contact = {
  facts: [email: string],
  data: {
    trusted: [name: string?, phone: string?],
    untrusted: [notes: string?, job_title: string?, company: string?, address: string?]
  },
  key: email,
  display: [name, { ref: "email" }, phone]
}

>> ── Email messages ──
>>
>> The most attack-relevant record. `body` and `subject` are untrusted
>> data; the planner display omits them entirely. The worker sees them
>> via the worker display mode. `attachments` is currently `data` —
>> the threat model flags #attachment-label-propagation [!] as a gap
>> where file taint labels may not flow through attachment references.
>> Verify before relying on attachment-labeled defenses.
>>
>> `recipients`, `cc`, `bcc` are fact arrays — each element carries
>> its own fact label, so per-element control-arg checks (no-send-to-
>> unknown) work correctly when these arrays are passed to send_email.
record @email_msg = {
  facts: [id_: handle, sender: string?, recipients: array?, cc: array?, bcc: array?],
  data: {
    trusted: [timestamp: string?, read: boolean?],
    untrusted: [subject: string?, body: string?, attachments: array?]
  },
  key: id_,
  display: {
    default: [{ handle: "id_" }, { ref: "sender" }, { mask: "recipients" }, subject, body, { mask: "cc" }, { mask: "bcc" }, attachments, timestamp, read],
    worker: [{ handle: "id_" }, { ref: "sender" }, { mask: "recipients" }, subject, body, { mask: "cc" }, { mask: "bcc" }, attachments, timestamp, read],
    planner: [{ ref: "id_" }, { ref: "sender" }, { mask: "recipients" }, { mask: "cc" }, { mask: "bcc" }, timestamp, read]
  }
}

>> ── Calendar events ──
>>
>> `title`, `description`, `location` are untrusted data — the planner
>> sees only structured fields (id, participants, start/end time,
>> all_day, status). This matches the threat model's Class 7 expectation
>> that planner never reads injected event content.
>>
>> Per Attack Class 5, the calendar tools' notification side-effect
>> means create_calendar_event and add_calendar_event_participants
>> are exfil channels — the participants array is the destination set
>> and must be handle-grounded. Per-element fact labels on the array
>> let no-send-to-unknown enforce per-element grounding.
record @calendar_evt = {
  facts: [id_: handle, participants: array?],
  data: {
    trusted: [start_time: string?, end_time: string?, all_day: boolean?, status: string?],
    untrusted: [title: string?, description: string?, location: string?]
  },
  key: id_,
  display: {
    default: [{ handle: "id_" }, { ref: "participants" }, title, description, start_time, end_time, location, all_day, status],
    worker: [{ handle: "id_" }, { ref: "participants" }, title, description, start_time, end_time, location, all_day, status],
    planner: [{ ref: "id_" }, { ref: "participants" }, start_time, end_time, all_day, status]
  }
}

>> ── Cloud drive files ──
>>
>> File `content` is untrusted data; the planner sees only metadata
>> (filename, owner, size, shared_with refs). The worker sees content
>> via the worker display mode and produces influenced output.
>>
>> `shared_with` is a fact field (so handles flow through it) but the
>> threat model notes (Class 1 share_file path) that share_file's
>> `email` arg is the destination — not `shared_with` — so positive
>> checks fire on the share_file controlArg, not on this field.
>> Per the threat model: id_ is the file_id control arg for append/
>> delete/share. shared_with elements are handle-bearing in tool results
>> and may flow into share_file's email control arg for re-sharing. But
>> filename and owner are never control args for any write tool — they're
>> content for the worker to read. Making them facts caused shelf writes
>> to fail because file tools return them as plain strings with no
>> handle-bearing projection.
record @file_entry = {
  facts: [id_: handle, shared_with: array?],
  data: {
    trusted: [filename: string?, owner: string?, size: number?, last_modified: string?],
    untrusted: [content: string?]
  },
  key: id_,
  display: {
    default: [{ handle: "id_" }, filename, owner, content, size, { ref: "shared_with" }, last_modified],
    worker: [{ handle: "id_" }, filename, owner, content, size, { ref: "shared_with" }, last_modified],
    planner: [{ ref: "id_" }, filename, owner, size, { ref: "shared_with" }, last_modified]
  }
}

record @datetime_context = {
  facts: [value: string],
  data: {
    trusted: [kind: string?]
  },
  key: value,
  display: [{ ref: "value" }, kind]
}

>> Planner/runtime input schema for outbound email. Recipient-style
>> fields are facts because they name notification destinations; the
>> content fields stay payload.
record @send_email_inputs = {
  facts: [recipients: array, cc: array?, bcc: array?],
  data: {
    trusted: [subject: string, attachments: array?],
    untrusted: [body: string]
  },
  correlate: false,
  optional_benign: [cc, bcc],
  validate: "strict"
}

>> Planner-facing create-calendar inputs in the new catalog shape.
>> `participants` is the only fact because it is the notification
>> destination set. Omitting it models the benign personal-event case;
>> providing it requires per-element grounding.
record @create_calendar_event_inputs = {
  facts: [participants: array?],
  data: {
    trusted: [title: string, start_time: string, end_time: string, location: string?],
    untrusted: [description: string?]
  },
  optional_benign: [participants],
  validate: "strict"
}

record @delete_email_inputs = {
  facts: [email_id: handle],
  data: [],
  validate: "strict"
}

record @cancel_calendar_event_inputs = {
  facts: [event_id: handle],
  data: [],
  validate: "strict"
}

record @calendar_reschedule_inputs = {
  facts: [event_id: handle],
  data: {
    trusted: [new_start_time: string, new_end_time: string?]
  },
  update: [new_start_time, new_end_time],
  validate: "strict"
}

record @add_calendar_event_participants_inputs = {
  facts: [participants: array, event_id: handle],
  data: [],
  correlate: false,
  validate: "strict"
}

record @file_append_inputs = {
  facts: [file_id: handle],
  data: {
    untrusted: [content: string]
  },
  validate: "strict"
}

>> File creation has no control args, but a dedicated strict input record
>> keeps the live tool catalog on the same new-shape contract as the
>> planner catalog.
record @file_create_inputs = {
  facts: [],
  data: {
    trusted: [filename: string],
    untrusted: [content: string]
  },
  validate: "strict"
}

record @delete_file_inputs = {
  facts: [file_id: handle],
  data: [],
  validate: "strict"
}

record @share_file_inputs = {
  facts: [email: string, file_id: handle],
  data: {
    trusted: [permission: string]
  },
  correlate: false,
  validate: "strict"
}

var @records = {
  contact: @contact,
  email_msg: @email_msg,
  calendar_evt: @calendar_evt,
  file_entry: @file_entry,
  datetime_context: @datetime_context,
  send_email_inputs: @send_email_inputs,
  delete_email_inputs: @delete_email_inputs,
  create_calendar_event_inputs: @create_calendar_event_inputs,
  cancel_calendar_event_inputs: @cancel_calendar_event_inputs,
  calendar_reschedule_inputs: @calendar_reschedule_inputs,
  add_calendar_event_participants_inputs: @add_calendar_event_participants_inputs,
  file_append_inputs: @file_append_inputs,
  file_create_inputs: @file_create_inputs,
  delete_file_inputs: @delete_file_inputs,
  share_file_inputs: @share_file_inputs
}

export {
  @contact,
  @email_msg,
  @calendar_evt,
  @file_entry,
  @datetime_context,
  @send_email_inputs,
  @delete_email_inputs,
  @create_calendar_event_inputs,
  @cancel_calendar_event_inputs,
  @calendar_reschedule_inputs,
  @add_calendar_event_participants_inputs,
  @file_append_inputs,
  @file_create_inputs,
  @delete_file_inputs,
  @share_file_inputs,
  @records
}
